  specified otherwise. The network of all those constraints that meet the three requirements of closure is, we hold, collectively able to self-determine through self-constraint. Note also that the second condition does not require direct
  dependence. The reason is that, while each constraint of
  
  <math display="inline" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
    <mi mathvariant="bold-script">C</mi>
  </math> does depend directly on another constraint included in the same set, it might (and usually does) contribute to indirectly
  generating other constraints, typically when several constraints act successively on a chain of processes. For example, the shape of proteins depends only indirectly on the m
  <span class="eccc1000-"><span class="small-caps">rna</span> </span>sequence since proteins mature in the endoplasmic reticulum.
</p>
